SOB 19 - Basic Circuits Used with Microcontrollers

This document describes pull-up resistors, pull-down resistors,
 voltage divider circuits and transistor-controlled motor circuits used with
 microcontrollers.

Pull-Up Resistor

Circuit: 5V -> 10kΩ resistor -> Input Pin;
Push button between Input Pin and GND.
The resistor keeps the input HIGH when the button is not pressed.
Pressing the button connects the pin to GND, making the input LOW.

Pull-Down Resistor

Circuit: Input Pin -> 10kΩ resistor -> GND;
Push button between Input Pin and 5V.
The resistor keeps the input LOW when the button is not pressed.
Pressing the button applies 5V, making the input HIGH.

Voltage Divider

Two resistors are connected in series between 5V and GND.
The output voltage is taken from the midpoint and read by an analogue input.
This allows sensors such as LDRs or thermistors to produce a variable voltage.

Motor Control Using Transistor

A DC motor is powered from an external supply.
An NPN transistor acts as a switch controlled by a microcontroller pin through a resistor.
A flyback diode is placed across the motor to protect the circuit from back EMF.

Interaction with the Microcontroller

Input circuits such as pull-up, pull-down and voltage divider networks provide
reliable voltage levels that can be read by digital or analogue pins.

Output circuits using transistors or relays allow the microcontroller to safely
control devices that require more current than the microcontroller can supply
directly.